body: Also created a feature request [to extend Flatten ops functionality](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/2046) in ONNX

Hi @dashesy ,

If I understand correctly, you would like ONNX Flatten to have a more generic spec (support `start_dim` and `end_dim`) and have it's corresponding implementation in ONNXRuntime. Is this a correct summary of this issue ?

Thanks!
Yes, currently ONNXRuntime does not have Flatten. And Flatten in ONNX is not generic enough either.

@dashesy - ONNXRuntime doe seem to have Flatten implementation - 
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/11243253f234e6b46d894acf8b112b6530edeafe/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/cpu_execution_provider.cc#L103

But it seems like the version support is only till opset 9. Let me fix that.

For the change in spec, it needs to be proposed to ONNX first. I ll propose a change in spec.

body:
Hi @dashesy ,

1) `Flatten` is implemented in the ONNXRuntime. So it should be part of ONNXRuntime 0.4.0. If you specific issues while trying to run an ONNX model with a `Flatten` op, please open a separate issue.  

2) Regarding the request for a more generic `Flatten` spec, I ll address this early next week, but let's use the feature request issue in ONNX to track the request. I will close this issue in ONNX RUntime and as soon as the generic spec of Flatten is accepted into ONNX - I will open up another task to track it's implementation here.

Thanks!

issue.title: flatten() is not ONNX exportable with dynamic axes

labels.name: triaged
labels.description: This issue has been looked at a team member, and triaged and prioritized into an appropriate module

repository.name: pytorch
repository.description: Tensors and Dynamic neural networks in Python with strong GPU acceleration

issue.body:
## Expected behavior

I would expect the following to not break

```python
import onnxruntime
import torch
import torch.nn as nn

class dummyNet(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(dummyNet, self).__init__()
        self.n =  nn.Conv2d(1, 35, 1)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.n(x)
        x = x.unsqueeze(1)
        x = x.permute(0, 1, 3, 2, 4).contiguous()
        x = x.flatten(3, 4)
        return x

n = dummyNet()
x = torch.randn(1,1,1024,2)
ort_x = torch.randn(1,1,4096,2).numpy()

torch.onnx.export(n,
                             (x,),
                             "d.onnx",
                             opset_version=12,
                             input_names=['in'],
                             output_names=['out'],
                             dynamic_axes={'in': [0, 2], 'out': [0,2]})

ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession("d.onnx")
ort_inputs = {}
ort_inputs[ort_session.get_inputs()[0].name] = ort_x
ort_outs = ort_session.run(None, ort_inputs)
```

If add the following lines
```
ort_inputs = ort_session.get_inputs()
print(ort_inputs[0].shape)
```
I get
```
['in_dynamic_axes_1', 1, 'in_dynamic_axes_2', 2]
```

So it thinks the batch dimension and height dimension are dynamic.
But if you run the code you get stack trace:
```
2020-08-13 07:13:26.266184390 [E:onnxruntime:, sequential_executor.cc:309 Execute] Non-zero status code returned while running Reshape node. Name:'Reshape_4' Status Message: /onnxruntime_src/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/tensor/reshape_helper.h:43 onnxruntime::ReshapeHelper::ReshapeHelper(const onnxruntime::TensorShape&, std::vector<long int>&) gsl::narrow_cast<int64_t>(input_shape.Size()) == size was false. The input tensor cannot be reshaped to the requested shape. Input shape:{1,1,4096,35,2}, requested shape:{1,1,1024,70}
```

So yes the error occurs in ONNXRUNTIME, but it is only doing what it is told, and the pytorch ONNX exporter has told it to flatten {1,1,4096,35,2} to {1,1,1024,70}
